svg:text.svg:tspan: The atmosphere contains 78% nitrogen gas, N. This is very unreactive and so
it can’t be used directly by plants or animals. Nitrogen is needed for making
proteins for growth, so living organisms have to get it somehow. This is where
the nitrogen cycle comes in — see Figure 1.
Nitrogen is taken out of the air
Nitrogen in the air has to be turned into mineral ions (such as ) in
the soil before plants can use it. The process of turning N from the air into
nitrogen-containing ions that plants can use is called nitrogen xation.
Nitrogen xation happens in two main ways. The rst involves lightning.
There’s so much energy in a bolt of lightning that it’s enough to make nitrogen
react with oxygen in the air to produce nitrates.

to the soil (see next page). Nitrogen-containing ions can also leak out of the
nodules during plant growth. The bacteria have a relationship

and the plants get nitrogen-containing ions from the bacteria to make
Plants absorb nitrogen-containing ions from the soil (or from their root
nodules in the case of legumes) and use the nitrogen in them to make
proteins. Nitrogen is then passed along food chains in the form of proteins,
as animals eat plants (and each other).
Like carbon and water, the nitrogen on Earth is constantly being recycled.
Humans are able to influence this cycle for our own benefit.
